4536adb0-f8f1-4bfe-886d-2cef86b56600.1bc68230-017c-45ff-93ec-e22e65bc7a31.description=
Reads the file specified in the source input parameter.  If Store is true, then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then subsequent calls to the operation results in the next line being returned.

Inputs\:
source - Path to the file to be read.
filter - Regular expression filter to be applied to each line (can be left blank for all).
store - Whether to store results in the session for retrieval. Valid values \: true,false
delimiter - If set to null, the file is read line by line, otherwise it is a delimiter placed between read lines (note, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size).
user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when reading.
password - Password for the user.
eofReset - If set to true than after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
characterSet - The character encoding used to read the file (for instance, windows-1252). The default is UTF-8.

Responses\:
more lines - More lines are available to be read in the session.
no more lines - No lines are available for reading in the session.
failure - If something went wrong. 

Results\:
returnResult - One line read from the file. New line characters are removed from the line read.
COUNT - On the first pass, the total number of lines matched.  On subsequent runs, the number of lines remaining in the session. This result is only returned in line-by-line mode.

Note\:
    If you are using UTF-8 special characters(for example japanese characters), please ensure that your file is encoded in UTF-8 and not in ANSI wich is the default file encoding in windows when you are creating a new file.

4536adb0-f8f1-4bfe-886d-2cef86b56600.373dc090-6890-4005-a599-7f9d4224f5f6.callout=POSRE hasta aquí 4536adb0-f8f1-4bfe-886d-2cef86b56600.38d26356-8e65-4284-a509-dfaf678be0f1.description=
This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Inputs\:
    source -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
    contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file.  
Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
    delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file.
Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. 
Default\: UTF-8. 
Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
    overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. 
Default\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise.
    exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - File/directory was written successfully.
    failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source.

Examples\:
1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\:
    source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\:
    source\: /root/example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,
